
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `dirname` baraye gereftan masire (path) yek file ya directory va hazfe name file az an estefade mishavad. Be ebarate digar, `dirname` directory ke file dar an gharar darad ra neshon midahad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `dirname --help` --> ❓ Namayeshe rahnamaye dastoor
    🔹 `dirname --version` --> ℹ️ Namayeshe version dastoor

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ dirname /home/user/documents/file.txt

    🔹 Output: /home/user/documents

    $ dirname /usr/bin/

    🔹 Output: /usr

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ dirname ./myfile.txt

    🔹 Agar `myfile.txt` dar hamin directory-e shoma bashad, natije "." khahad bood, yani directory-e konuni.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `dirname` command extracts the directory path from a given filename or directory path. It essentially removes the trailing filename component, leaving just the path to the directory containing the file.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `dirname --help` --> ❓ Display help information
    🔹 `dirname --version` --> ℹ️ Display version information

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ dirname /home/user/documents/file.txt

    🔹 Output: /home/user/documents

    $ dirname /usr/bin/

    🔹 Output: /usr

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ dirname ./myfile.txt

    🔹 If `myfile.txt` is in your current directory, the output will be ".", representing the current directory.

